<$fill $name="body">

!! What it does

Discovers binary files (PDF, DOCX, XLSX, images, etc.) in configured subdirectory structures and creates `_canonical_uri` tiddlers for them at boot. Files are served via a custom HTTP route — no manual `tiddlywiki.files` per directory needed.

!! How it works

# At boot, reads profile definitions from `$:/config/rimir/scattered-binaries/profiles`
# For each profile, scans the configured base path for directories matching `dirPattern`
# Within matched directories, recursively scans the `subFolder` for binary files
# Cleans up any boot-loaded tiddlers with absolute filepath titles (TW boot scanner artifacts)
# Creates `_canonical_uri` tiddlers with clean titles and configured tags
# Stores profile data for the HTTP route module
# The route module serves files on demand, with path traversal protection and extension filtering

!! Security

* Path traversal protection via `path.relative()` check on every request
* Only files with known binary extensions are served (`.pdf`, `.docx`, `.xlsx`, etc.)
* No directory listing — must know exact filename
* `dirPattern` regex is validated at boot (malformed patterns are skipped with a warning)
* Files with `.meta` sidecars are skipped (defers to TW's native handling)

</$fill>
</$transclude>
